# =============================================================================
# ABStrack — environment template (safe to commit; no real secrets)
# =============================================================================
#
# Where to copy values
# --------------------
# | Copy these variables into...              | Used when running...              |
# |-------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------|
# | apps/web/.env.local                       | User web app (Next.js)            |
# | apps/practitioner/.env.local              | Practitioner web app (Next.js)  |
# | apps/mobile/.env                          | Mobile app (Expo / Metro)         |
#
# Next.js reads `.env.local` from each app directory (not the repo root).
# Expo loads `.env` from `apps/mobile/` (see Expo env docs).
#
# Mobile vs Next variable names
# -----------------------------
# Expo only embeds **`EXPO_PUBLIC_*`** into the JS bundle. It does **not** treat
# `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` like Next.js does — those names in `apps/mobile/.env` are
# ignored by Expo (unless you read `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_*` yourself, which
# you should not rely on). When you create `apps/mobile/.env`, include **only**
# the `EXPO_PUBLIC_*` lines below (same URL and key as Next; different prefix).
# Omit the `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` block from that file to avoid confusion and noisy
# `env: export ...` logs from the Expo CLI.
#
# Supabase project (dev / staging)
# --------------------------------
# 1. Create a project: https://supabase.com/dashboard
# 2. Authentication → Providers → enable **Email** (email + password), per PRD §1.
# 3. Keys: Supabase dashboard → **Settings** → **API Keys** (or the project Connect dialog).
#    Prefer the platform **publishable** key (`sb_publishable_...`) and **secret**
#    key (`sb_secret_...`) over legacy JWT **anon** / **service_role** keys.
#    See: https://supabase.com/docs/guides/api/api-keys
#
# Pass the publishable key (or legacy anon) as the second argument to
# `createClient(url, key)` in client code; same RLS behavior.
#
# Secret key (`sb_secret_...` → `SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY`): server-only for
# `@abstrack/supabase/admin`. Never `NEXT_PUBLIC_*`, `EXPO_PUBLIC_*`, or client bundles.
# Found in the Supabase UI under **Settings → API Keys** (secret key row; not the publishable key).
#
# Legacy JWT anon keys may still be used for **client** `createClient` during migration;
# this repo does not define a `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` env — use the dashboard secret key only.
#
# Edge Functions: publishable/secret keys have JWT verification caveats vs
# legacy keys — see the “Known limitations” section in the API keys doc above.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- Next.js (apps/web, apps/practitioner) — safe to expose in the browser bundle
# apps/web Supabase SSR utilities use publishable key first, then fall back to legacy anon key.
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://YOUR_PROJECT_REF.supabase.co
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=sb_publishable_your_key

# apps/practitioner: set `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_NAME` so the TOTP issuer in authenticator apps matches
# your product name per environment. If unset, the issuer falls back to "ABStrack".
# Supabase may embed `localhost` in its otpauth URI; practitioner builds the QR locally from the secret.
# Does not replace Supabase Dashboard → Authentication → URL Configuration (Site URL).
NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_NAME=ABStrack

# --- Expo (apps/mobile) — inlined at bundle time; same values as Next
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://YOUR_PROJECT_REF.supabase.co
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=sb_publishable_your_key

# --- Server-only (optional; uncomment when a server route or script imports @abstrack/supabase/admin)
# SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY=sb_secret_your_key

# --- Legacy publishable slot only (optional — until you use sb_publishable_* everywhere)
# NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...

# --- Shared packages (@abstrack/supabase, future PowerSync wiring)
# Libraries read `process.env` from the consuming app’s bundle or Node context.
# They do not load this file by themselves — set the variables in the app
# `.env.local` / `.env` as appropriate for that platform’s naming rules.
